I=E2=80=99m using urxvt as well (rxvt-unicode-256color, to be specific), fo=
r many
years, and can=E2=80=99t quite seem to make the switch to anything else whe=
never I
try :)

Regarding copy & paste, urxvt=E2=80=99s mouseless mark and yank comes in ha=
ndy to
open URLs and anything like URLs:
https://github.com/bartman/urxvt-scripts/blob/master/mark-and-yank

Whenever I want to ultimately continue working with the output of a command
in my text editor, I=E2=80=99ve come to prefer making my editor execute tha=
t
command and insert its output, possibly in a scratch buffer. For more
interactive sessions, modern editors typically have shell support (e.g. M-x
shell in Emacs) and may offer easy copy & paste to/from the shell.

On Thu, Aug 8, 2019 at 1:39 PM Jeff Abrahamson <jeff@p27.eu> wrote:

> On 08/08/2019 12:25, Lu=C3=AD=C2=ADs Moreira de Sousa (Redacted sender
> luis.de.sousa for DMARC) wrote:
> > Hi everyone,
> >
> > I have been using i3 with some degree of success for a few months. As
> > intended, I greatly reduced the use of the mouse. However, there is a
> > programme I constantly use that often requires interaction with the
> > mouse: GNOME terminal. To select output excerpts and copy them to the
> > clipboard there is no alternative to the mouse.
> >
> > What terminal programme(s) you use together with i3? Can you use a
> > terminal fully without the mouse?
>
>
> Hi, Lu=C3=ADs.
>
> I remember using gnome terminal and finding it strangely mouse intensive.
>
> I use urxvt, for which the ubuntu package, anyway, is rxvt-unicode.  It
> exists in multiple variations (cf. dpkg -L rxvt-unicode | grep bin) and
> offers a terminal server daemon.  I've not taken the time to dig through
> the extensive documentation beyond what I needed when I first started
> using it.
>
> You don't indicate in your mail if you're thinking of copy/paste, for
> which I find the mouse convenient, but urxvt does have some support for
> interacting with the X clipboard.  You might also find the utility xclip
> of interest if this is one of your pain points.  Also, the
> recommendation to use tmux or screen is quite good for many reasons
> beyond simple copy/paste.  (Probably choose tmux over screen if you have
> no history with either, but this is open to disagreement.)
>
